Alaska Department of Education and Early Development
July 30 at 3:00 PM ·

Join Chief Medical Officer Dr. Annezinkmd and Commissioner Johnson next Tuesday, August 4th as DEED kicks off this month-long professional development opportunity for Alaska's community of learners. The series of informational sessions will address both the educational and medical challenges of COVID-19. Teaching and learning must be the constant - everything else is a variable.

This opportunity is open to educators, school district staff, parents, students, school board members, tribal and thought leaders, and anyone wanting to be involved in the discussion around the 2020-2021 school year.

Register at: aklearns.org/smartwebinar/

If you're ready to send your child back to school, we're ready to have them

post_text: We know that many of the virtual educational programs in the state and across the country last spring (including ours) were not what we, or parents, had hoped they would be. I want to be clear that AGSD is NOT doing a repeat of that again. All summer AGSD has been developing an instructional model that will be used in both the classroom and in our HomeLink Classroom. This will help to ensure that there will be minimal disruption, no matter what. We have also been redesigning our Special Education Services program so that Admin is better able to manage and track services, and to be more responsive to the need of our students and families. For more information, and to learn about our HomeLink Classroom, please feel free to call Superintendent MacManus, or your principal.
text: We know that many of the virtual educational programs in the state and across the country last spring (including ours) were not what we, or parents, had hoped they would be. This will help to ensure that there will be minimal disruption, no matter what. We have also been redesigning our Special Education Services program so that Admin is better able to manage and track services, and to be more responsive to the need of our students and families. For more information, and to learn about our HomeLink Classroom, please feel free to call Superintendent MacManus, or your principal.

post_text:
Today is School Principal's Day. AGSD has an extraordinary team of principals who have an incredibly difficult job. I am proud of our administrative team, and encourage everyone to thank them, and acknowledge the selfless work that they do for our kids, and we echo the words of our Department of Education Commissioner Johnson.

"From the beginning of this crisis we have asked educators not to wait for direction, but to make decisions quickly that are focused on the safety and best interest of students and families. Our principals across the state are knocking it out of the park and raising the bar for everybody," said Commissioner Johnson. "It’s a good thing for our students."

post_text: By way of clarification, of the Governors Health Mandate #13 which extends school closures to the end of the year, only impacts school buildings being open for regular operations. While our buildings are closed to the public, food service will also be continuing, teachers will still be working with our families, and the district will still be supporting our communities. There remains a lot of learning yet to take place between now and the end of the school year.

post_text:
How long does COVID live on various surfaces? This is IMPORTANT to know. Paper materials that go home from AGSD will come out of the copier (UV Light), handled with gloves, and then allowed to sit for 24 to 48 hours before being sent out. The virus that causes coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) is stable for several hours to days in aerosols and on surfaces, according to a new study from National Institutes of Health, CDC, UCLA and Princeton University scientists in The New England Journal of Medicine. The scientists found that severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2) was detectable in aerosols for up to three hours, up to four hours on copper, up to 24 hours on cardboard and up to two to three days on plastic and stainless steel.

https://www.nih.gov/news-events/news-releases/new-coronavirus-stable-hours-surfaces

post_text:
To the communities of Alaska Gateway School District.
There is a plan to address the COVID-19 Pandemic. It is a very simple plan that will work, if we will only all follow it.
- Wash your hands and all common touch areas
- Keep your distance from people as much possible
- Do not travel unless you must
- Isolate yourself if you do
- If you have symptoms isolate yourself and call the clinic
- Keep groups small...under 5
- Wash your hands

This is all we have to do, for a few short weeks...just follow that plan. ALL OF US! Because then, everyone who has COVID-19 can be discovered, and can be isolated, and our medical professionals will be able to do their jobs to help them, and years from now this will only be dim memory. It's not hard...and we can do this! Do it because you love your communities. Right now, everyone needs to just follow the plan, and we can all help save thousands and thousands of lives.

Please, just follow the plan!

Scott MacManus, Superintendent.

post_text:
Food Service Start Schedule

AGSD Food service pickups and deliveries during the mandated school closure are scheduled to begin on Wednesday, March 25th. We are working our menus, increasing sanitizing procedures, lining up work assignments, and getting the system figured out for deliveries.

If anyone has additional children under the age of 18 in their homes, the school district is committed to providing food service to them. Please call your school on Monday and let them know. If you have any critical needs in your home please let your school know, and we will see what we can do to help.

I am very proud of our cooks and those who have volunteered to do food deliveries, who are critically important to providing lunches and breakfasts to our children. If you have any questions about food service in your community, please contact your school principal. We are doing our best to figure this all out so that everyone gets what they need.

In the meantime, for our families who have internet access, we would like to make sure that our K-12 students are able to continue to use the great digital learning programs they have been using in their classrooms. We are creating digital info sheets for each student in the district that includes their usernames and passwords, as well as URL addresses to their programs.

If you would like to have this info for your child(ren), please send us an email at onlineprograms@agsd.us and tell us the names (first and last) of your children who you'd like these info sheets for. We will reply to your email with the attached info sheets for each of your children.

Please give us a little time to respond. We anticipate being able reply to you by the end of the day on Friday at the latest.

post_text:
AGSD Administration worked today on preparing for the return of staff after Springbreak, and spooling up for the work that our certified and classified staff will have to do once they return.

I'd like all AGSD staff to know that there will be much work that has to be done, and that we will be coordinating with each department and school site. There has been some understandable fear that staff may not be able to work and get their regular paycheck, which is important, and that they count on. While you may not be working with students when you come back, we are organizing the work that has to be done to meet our mission of educating students, so that everyone who wants to and who can, will have the opportunity to work and not lose their paycheck.

For the Alaska Heat high school hockey team, the player pool is geographically gigantic

Lisa Murkowski
February 11 at 12:16 PM ·

Because of the remote nature of our rural communities, something as simple as getting together for a sports practice can be a real challenge. From braving negative temperatures and traveling hundreds of miles just to get some practice time in with their teammates, this article shows some of the length Alaskans go through just to play the sports that they love. #OnlyInAlaska
